review_blob: UPDATED: MAY 6, 2016
Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. Boozy and warming, spicy and strong. Smooth and nice. Some candy, some jam. Barrel is there but not overdone, vanilla too. Very drinkable.
Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. Strong and boozy fruity berries. Not really like the Belgian quads I know. Feasty. Good carbonation. Sweet, but not too extreme. Good, but not as complex as quads can be.
beer_name: Dieu du Ciel Rigor Mortis Abt

review_blob: Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. A beautiful to get wasted! Plums, prunes, dried fruit. Strong and powerful, sweet and smooth, a bit boozy. Very very nice!

Can, courtesy of SinH4. Wow, this is coconut! No comparison to that weak chocolate bar with coconut... Besides a very, very decent porter. Light but not boring. Dry chocolate cake. Very drinkable. Smooth.
beer_name: Oskar Blues / Shamrock Death By Coconut

review_blob: Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. Quite boring for a Weizen from Munich. Some wheat, low yeast and banana, no clover. Low carbonation. Okay.
Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. Citric and little soapy. Light and refreshing. Slightly oily. Good carbonation, smooth. Okay.

Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. Might be a bit too warm, but this smells like the leftovers after cleaning dishes. Dirty, a bit soapy and some citrus. Tongue and palate are great though, bitter and powerful, with a good malt body. If it werent for that nose, this would be really good.
beer_name: Schoppe Bru Flower Power Session IPA

beer_brewer_name: Birra Nursia - Monastero di San Benedetto da Norcia
review_blob: Bottle. Looks very muddy. Lots of yeast, too. Some late citrus. Sweetish but dirty. Okay carbonation, opening up the beer a little bit. Not interesting, but very drinkable.
Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. Refreshing, flowery, buttery, highly drinkable. Yeast-forward, pleasant banana. Nice!
Bottle from Beersnmore. Lots of cherry, dry chocolate, sour and sweet. Very intense, almost too extreme. Harmony is borderline, but it does work.
Bottle, courtesy of SinH4. Slightly hoppy, grainy, fruity, yet clearly no pale ale. A bit flat, lacking carbonation. Okay.
beer_name: CREW Republic / Herzl X Steam Beer

review_blob: 75cl bottle from Beersnmore, as BATS. Very lightly smoked, but present. Hints of sourness, otherwise malt-forward. Fruity, little cherries, peach, green tea (?). Low bitterness, low carbonation, but its not lacking. Okay.

Bottle from Beersnmore. Beautiful roast aroma of fresh coffee beans with a healthy amount of recently opened walnut. Perfect harmony between these two dominating aromas throughout. Some caramel and chocolate too, but less obvious. The heavy flavours become light on the tongue as the carbonation smoothes them out. Long finish, with lingering coffee. Incredible drinkability. Needs some air to open up, but when it does, its a bomb!
Bottle, from Coop. Tropical and almost artificially sweet, yet also incredibly bitter. Too thick hick and oily for what it offers. Solid malts, yet not balanced. Drinkable.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Might be a bit too old, best before [in 3 weeks]. Nicely flowery, but also some onion and butter. Unbalanced.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Very, very sweet. Sticky. Almost artificial. Pine, candy. Okay.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Lots and lots of banana and booze, warming and creamy. Short finish. Fruity.
beer_name: Schneider Weisse Tap X Maries Rendezvous

review_blob: Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Hoppy and dark indeed, but it lacks direction and balance. Sweeter than it should be. Dominant bitterness, but not as a single characteristic. Okay.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Bottle basically exploded upon opening, way way overcarbonated. Has the malt for a bock, but it suffers under the carbonation. Way off balance.
beer_name: Birrificio di Franciacorta 18.80 Birra Rossa Bock

review_blob: Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. A nice but also easy red ale. Some caramel, some fruit, but it could be a bit more daring. Matching carbonation, suitable malts, okay balance. Quite enjoyable.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. A nice and hoppy pale ale, quite bitter. Grassy, spring-like, refreshing.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Sweet honey aroma with a matching crisp carbonation and the necessary malts to support it. Bready texture. Nice.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Lots and lots of ripe banana throughout. Creamy texture behind a bubbly carbonation. Sweet finish, could be drier. Good!
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Some corn notes, very light and crisp, refreshing. Not daring, but a cream ale doesnt really need that. Some grassy hops aroma. Okay.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Aroma of honey indeed. Dominant bitterness over the usual lack of malts and hops in Swiss craft. Thus a bit flat and boring.

Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Vanilla, banana, liquor, booze, coffee. A bit artificial, but also strong in flavours without being heavy. Late bitterness. Could be a tad heavier, but generally very nice.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. Low spice, not much aroma. Mostly bitter with a low taste, little fruit. A bit metallic, more in mouthfeel than taste. Meh.
Bottle at Erzbierschof Monday Club. A light spring beer, but a rather unbalanced one. Aggressive carbonation followed by some Hagebutte sourness, but very low. No harmony.

Bottle, from the 523 web shop. Unsurprisingly similar to the Sloane Steady. The yeast makes a difference though: More grass, more summer aroma. Propels more hop aromas throughout. Carbonation is more aggressive, killing more flavours and making it less refreshing. Still some farmhouse aromas, but definitely less. I liked the other, softer one better.

Bottle from the 523 web shop. A light Belgian ale with some farmhouse indeed, but not so much actually. Crisp carbonation, but not as overwhelming as others. Refreshing. Some stables aroma, slightly citric, but rather not daring anything. A convincing take on a farmhouse Belgian, but not an overwhelming one.

Bottle, courtesy of Benzai during EuroSwap 1/2016. Sweet aroma, almost like a sweet or milk stout. Slightly boozy, but warming and thus not irritating at all. A bit lactic. Not quite as overwhelming as I feared, pleasant to drink for such a heavy beer.

Bottle from Beersnmore. Orange: Check. Porter: Check. Yuzu? Well, never heard of it. I can find tangerine, lemon, orange, grapefruit. Very refreshing, with that bitterness of a grapefruit on the tongue. Refreshing and light while still showing off the porter roast. Good.
beer_name: Mikkeller Orange Yuzu Glad I Said Porter

review_blob: Bottle, courtesy of Benzai during EuroSwap 1/2016. Pours dark brown with a short-lived but beautiful head. An imperial porter that lives up to its style: Dark but not burnt, strong and heavy, yet not overdone. Caramel and toffee aroma, pleasant texture and carbonation. Only slightly boozy, but also nicely warming.

Bottle from Beersnmore. Is this an actual beer? Has the air of milk lemonade. Pinchy sour, very crisply carbonated (and lots of it), mostly lemon aroma, but barely anything besides that. Well, it is a bit lactic, too. A bubbly lemon-milky lemonade, so to say. Probably good on a really hot summer day.
Tap at Erzbierschof Zurich. An IIPA with lots of residual sweetness and booze, but both dont carry so much. Some pine needles, some resin, some. Heavy, almost greasy.
beer_name: Benford / Evil Twin The Problem Solver

review_blob: Tap at Erzbierschof Zurich. Light, mostly citric, some tropical fruits. Low sweetness, mostly bitter. Oily texture, could take some more carbonation.

Bottle from Beersnmore. On a blind tasting I probably wouldnt notice this is a coffee IPA. Traces are there, but not so much in aroma, rather in texture and palate. Besides that a typical IPA, although with a rather low carbonation, a bit bready. Okay.

Bottle from Beersnmore. An unusual IPA indeed. Aromatic nose of pine, low fruits. Dominant bitterness, slightly buffered by a carbonation that turns crisp quite late in the mouth. An okay take on a red IPA, but not my favourite.

Bottle from Erzbierschof Zurich. A typical medium-ABV Alesmith: Nutty, pines, some caramel, rather malt-dominated, and incredibly drinkable! Doesnt go in any particular style direction as other beers, hardly recognizable as an ESB. Not overly complex, but otherwise this beer does many things right: Texture, carbonation, balance, palate...

Bottle from Biervana. A saison imitating to be Belgian, as promised: Sweet, some farmhouse, crisp but fine carbonation making it not quite as heavy as it might be, a bit oily. Quite bitter. Nice, but not terribly exciting by taste.

Bottle, 2014 vintage, 750ml. Pours clear dark red with a healthy head that dies quickly. Good cherries, not overwhelming, some funk too. Carbonation is crisp, especially after swallowing. Some vinegar on the palate that doesnt really fit so well. Altogether a fine mix of things to discover, but not the most harmonic one.

Bottle from Erzbierschof Zurich. A very smooth and drinkable pale ale indeed. Spring-like aroma hops give this beer a fresh feeling, carbonation and malts are matching. Pines, some citrus. Medium-bodied, but never boring. Keeps its thing throughout. This beer does literally nothing wrong, yet it fails to excite me. It is very, very solid though.
Can from Beersnmore. Some bacon-y smoke, but really mostly a chocolate porter. Sweet, bitter, but not burnt. Carbonation makes this beer quite light without killing the aromas. Nice!

Can from Beersnmore. Ah, finally a hoppy BIPA again. Lots of dark roast malts, a solid refreshing hops note, with a decent carbonation and a fizzy texture balancing out everything while making it nice and fresh. Good brew!

Can from Beersnmore. A fat an healthy heavy IPA with indeed some rye character. It falls off behind the dense aroma and taste, but is still noticeable. Lots of residual sweetness next to some tropical fruits and a healthy carbonation. Very nice!
Tap at ZBF 2016. Dirty but sweet pale ale. Not so balanced and rather watery. Meh.
Tap at ZBF 2016. Aroma of industrial vanilla ice cream. Pretty atypical for an IPA in general, not much malts, low bitterness. Meh.
Tap at ZBF 2016. Soft bacony smoke on the nose, slightly greasy, soft chili hotness on the palate. Well balanced, but not overly exciting.
Tap at ZBF 2016. A really refreshing lager with lots of melon aroma. Crisp carbonation. Well done indeed!
